                     <interp inst="def1-1407-18420404" type="surname" value="JONES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1407-18420404" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">JOHN JONES</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18420404-1407-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18420404-1407-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18420404-1407-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="housebreaking"></interp>for feloniously breaking and enter<lb></lb>ing the dwelling-house of <persName id="t18420404-name-1445" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18420404-name-1445" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420404-name-1445" type="surname" value="ATCHISON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420404-name-1445" type="given" value="EDWARD MASTERS"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18420404-1407-offence-1 t18420404-name-1445"></join>Edward Masters Atchison</persName>, on the <rs id="t18420404-cd-247" type="crimeDate">
                        <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18420404-1407-offence-1 t18420404-cd-247"></join>4th of April</rs>. at <placeName id="t18420404-geo-27">
                        <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18420404-1407-offence-1 t18420404-geo-27"></join>St. Mary, Newington</placeName>, and stealing therein 1 coat, value 2<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., 1 waistcoat, value 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., and 1 pair of trowsers, value 1<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., the goods of <persName id="t18420404-name-1446" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18420404-name-1446" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420404-name-1446" type="surname" value="DEHAY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420404-name-1446" type="given" value="THOMAS POLLUX"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18420404-1407-offence-1 t18420404-name-1446"></join>Thomas Pollux Dehay</persName>.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420404-name-1447" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420404-name-1447" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420404-name-1447" type="surname" value="DEHAY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420404-name-1447" type="given" value="THOMAS POLLUX"></interp>THOMAS POLLUX DEHAY</persName>
                  </hi>. I live at No. 18, Bedford-terrace, in the parish of St. Mary, Newington. On the 4th of April, about ten minutes before ten o'clock in the morning, I left my house—I only have the back-room ground-floor—the door opens into the passage, leading to the street</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184204040245"></xptr>
               <p>—Mr. Edward Masters Atchison, the landlord, lives in the house—he occupies the room below—the floor is let to lodgers—there is another floor above that, which the landlord occupies—I returned about two o'clock in the morning—I had left a coat and waistcoat on the sideboard in the room—I did not lock my door myself—I left it open—when I got up in the morning I missed my coat, waistcoat, and trowsers—I saw them in the possession of the officer.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420404-name-1448" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420404-name-1448" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420404-name-1448" type="surname" value="MAYCOCK"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420404-name-1448" type="given" value="ELIZABETH"></interp>ELIZABETH MAYCOCK</persName>
                  </hi>. I live at No. 15, Bedford-terrace, Newington—I had charge of the keys of No. 18—I went there on the 4th of April, at four o'clock in the afternoon, to call Mr. Atchison out, and found nobody but him at home—he is a compositor on the "Times"—he left his house about ten minutes after four o'clock, and came into my house and took tea, leaving nobody in the house—he locked the door after him, and I went there again about a quarter to seven o'clock as the keys were left in my possession—I went into every room and found everything correct—I went into the prose<lb></lb>cutor's room—I did not notice anything there particular—when I came out I locked the door, the windows were all fastened, and I took the key of the door home with me—in consequence of information I went to the house again in ten minutes or a quarter of an hour—I found the street door locked as I had left it, but the back door wide open—it opens into the garden—the door was bolted top and bottom when I left—it must have been opened from within—I found Mr. Dehay's room door wide open, but missed nothing myself—I had left his room door locked, with the key outside.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420404-name-1449" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420404-name-1449" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420404-name-1449" type="surname" value="CHURCH"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420404-name-1449" type="given" value="ANN"></interp>ANN CHURCH</persName>
                  </hi>. I live at No. 8, Victoria-terrace, exactly opposite Mr. Atchison's house. On the 4th of April, about one o'clock, I saw three very suspicious characters about Mr. Atchison's house; and again about half-past seven o'clock in the evening I saw a man knock re<lb></lb>peatedly at the front-door—nobody answered it—and between seven and eight o'clock I saw a man, I cannot say whether it was the same, enter the house and shut the door after him—I cannot say whether he did any<lb></lb>thing before entering the house—I saw nobody else about the house at that time—I immediately went to give information.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420404-name-1450" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420404-name-1450" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420404-name-1450" type="surname" value="RULER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420404-name-1450" type="given" value="THOMAS NICHOLSON"></interp>THOMAS NICHOLSON RULER</persName>
                  </hi>. I live at No. 2, West-terrace, St. George's-row—I know Mr. Atchison's house—there is a back yard to my house which is about fifty feet from Mr. Atchison's back yard—it crosses a ditch and a wide garden—on the evening of the 4th of April I saw the prisoner in my yard, on my back premises—I went up to him and asked what he did on the premises—he said he was sent there—I asked him who sent him—he said he was sent through our house—I asked him what that was on his arm, he had some wearing apparel on his arm—he said it was his own property—I took him into the house and my father sent for a policeman, who came and took the property and some skeleton keys from him—he took him into custody—he had a coat and a pair of trowsers on his arm—I went back into the yard and saw footsteps in a direction from the back wall of Mr. Atchison's, across the garden ground to our premises—they were recently made—I did not find any other articles myself.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420404-name-1451" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420404-name-1451" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420404-name-1451" type="surname" value="COOK"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420404-name-1451" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN COOK</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable N</hi> 8.) On the evening of the 4th of April I was sent for to Ruler's house, and took the prisoner into custody—I found two skeleton keys up his coat sleeve, and a tin box with lucifers, and a candle in it—Ruler said there was a coat and trowsers belonging to him—the prisoner was outside the door when I took him, and I saw the</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184204040246"></xptr>
               <p>things lying down in the passage—I left them in Ruler's care, and took the prisoner to the station—I afterwards examined Mr. Atchison's premises—I went in at the front door, got a candle, and went out at the back, and found this waistcoat in the back yard—I have had it ever since—I traced footsteps from Mr. Atchison's back yard wall, across the garden into Ruler's premises—I tried the skeleton keys to the lock of the front door next morning, and the largest opened it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner.</hi> When you took me in charge you took me outside the door; the clothes were in the house; the landlord brought them to the station, and said I had stolen them—I was taken with the two keys in my hand, which I had just picked up. <hi rend="italic">Witness.</hi> The keys were up his sleeve—I had a hard matter to get them out.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420404-name-1452" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420404-name-1452" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420404-name-1452" type="surname" value="RULER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420404-name-1452" type="given" value="THOMAS NICHOLSON"></interp>THOMAS NICHOLSON RULER</persName>
                  </hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">re-examined.</hi> When I met the prisoner in the yard, he had the trowsers and coat over his arm—before the policeman came, the coat and trowsers had dropped off his arm in the scuffle, and fell in the passage—I afterwards saw the policeman take possession of the same coat and waistcoat—as soon as my father said, "Send for a police<lb></lb>man," the prisoner scuffled to get away.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420404-name-1453" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420404-name-1453" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420404-name-1453" type="surname" value="DEHAY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420404-name-1453" type="given" value="THOMAS POLLUX"></interp>THOMAS POLLUX DEHAY</persName>
                  </hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">re-examined.</hi> This coat, waistcoat, and trow<lb></lb>sers are mine—I know the coat by its general appearance—there is no mark on it—I had it about three months—I know the trowsers and waist<lb></lb>coat in the same way—I have no mark on them—I believe them to be mine, and what I left in the house that day.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner's Defence.</hi> When the policeman took me, he took me outside the door, with two keys in my hand; the policeman brought the clothes to the station; he went back to the garden to see if he could see anything more; the man went first to trace footmarks, and he saw no waistcoat there; the policeman goes afterwards and finds one; they said at the station that I jumped over a wall fifteen feet high; is it likely I could do that and over a ditch? the keys I picked up by chance, and had them in my hand; they wanted to take them from me, but I would not give them to anybody but the policeman; they dragged me along and almost strangled me; when the policeman came I said I would go with him—I went to ask for the name of Jones, who I was directed to.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="largeCaps">
                     <rs id="t18420404-1407-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
                        <interp inst="t18420404-1407-verdict-1" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420404-1407-verdict-1" type="verdictSubcategory" value="no_subcategory"></interp>GUILTY</rs>
                  </hi>. Aged 23.—
<rs id="t18420404-1407-punishment-256" type="punishmentDescription">
